      Where are the =E2=80=A6=C2=A0oh, right, there.
   =20
 =20
Just a good headline from the Financial Times here, =E2=80=9CJefferies boss=
 sells $65mn in stock to buy a customer=E2=80=99s yacht=E2=80=9D:Jefferies =
chief executive Rich Handler has sold $65mn of his stock in the Wall Street=
 investment bank to buy a luxury yacht from longtime client Tilman Fertitta=
.Handler said on Wednesday that he had sold 1.5mn shares, about 7 per cent =
of his total holdings in Jefferies, at $43.50 each. This was the first time=
 he has sold shares in the bank other than for charitable or tax purposes.J=
efferies said Handler, 62, was using the cash to buy a boat and pay tax obl=
igations. A person familiar with the matter said the boat was a Westport 16=
4ft yacht being purchased from Fertitta, the hospitality billionaire.=E2=80=
=9CMy sale of shares today was a gift to myself and my family, and I do not=
 intend to sell any further shares,=E2=80=9D Handler said in a statement.Th=
ere is sort of a norm that executive stock sales are bad, because they are =
signs of bearishness: If you=E2=80=99re the CEO and you=E2=80=99re selling =
your company=E2=80=99s stock, people assume you think the stock will go dow=
n. And so when executives do sell big chunks of stock, they often try to ju=
stify the sales as not being about valuation. The classic justifications ha=
ve the form =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t want to sell my stock, but I had to=
=E2=80=9D (divorce, tax obligations
  [1]
), or else =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t want to sell my stock, but I had a rea=
lly compelling opportunity to make the world better=E2=80=9D (charitable do=
nations, buying Twitter Inc.).But =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t want to sell th=
e stock, but I saw a really cool yacht=E2=80=9D is also a pretty good justi=
fication? Like I do not think that this reflects much on Handler=E2=80=99s =
view of Jefferies=E2=80=99=C2=A0valuation. He wanted a little treat for him=
self, and there was that yacht.Also I suppose it is good customer service f=
or an investment bank=E2=80=99s CEO to occasionally buy a customer=E2=80=99=
s yacht from him? You don=E2=80=99t want your investment bankers to be=C2=
=A0too=C2=A0ostentatiously well-paid =E2=80=94=C2=A0it suggests that they=
=E2=80=99re overcharging =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if a good customer wants to unl=
oad one yacht, you want him to think of you first. =E2=80=9CImportant peopl=
e like to deal with important people,=E2=80=9D Goldman Sachs Group Inc. tel=
ls its bankers: =E2=80=9CAre you one?=E2=80=9D If you=E2=80=99re buying his=
 yacht, you probably are.
